The CMB is a snapshot of the universe at a redshift of about 1000, and it provides a wealth of information about the properties of the early universe. Magnetic fields can affect the CMB by polarizing photons, which can be detected as a small but measurable change in the temperature and anisotropy of the CMB. This effect is known as the Sunyaev-Zel'dovich effect, and it has been observed in a variety of galaxy clusters.

Cosmic magnetic fields also have important effects on the ionization history of the universe. The ionization of hydrogen and helium atoms is a crucial process in the evolution of the universe, as it sets the stage for the formation of the first structures. Magnetic fields can affect the ionization rate by causing the photons to scatter, which can change the rate at which hydrogen and helium atoms are ionized. This effect has been observed in a variety of objects, such as quasars and active galactic nuclei.

