Here's a possible implementation to create a new process using the `fork()` system call and then execute a shell command in the child process:
```c
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    while (1) {
        // Create a new process
        pid_t pid = fork();

        // Check if the fork was successful
        if (pid == -1) {
            perror("fork");
            exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
        } else if (pid == 0) {
            // Child process
            execl("/bin/sh", "sh", "-c", "ls", NULL);
        } else {
            // Parent process
            int status;
            waitpid(pid, &status, 0);
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```
In this code, the `fork()` system call is used to create a new process. The `fork()` function creates a new process by creating a copy of the calling process, including its memory and execution context. The returned value of `fork()` is the pid of the new process.

If the `fork()` is successful, the child process executes the `execl()` system call to replace the current process image with the `/bin/sh` binary, and then execute the command `ls` to list the files in the current directory.

If the `fork()` is not successful, the parent process waits for the child process to terminate using the `waitpid()` system call and the `status` variable is used to store the exit status of the child process.

Note that this code is just an example and it may not work as is, it's important to test and validate the code in your specific use case.

